==English==

===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|ML.|dēcrepitō}}, from {{der|en|la|dē-}} + {{m|la|crepitō}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/dɪˈkɹɛpɪteɪt/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[roast]] (a [[salt]] or [[mineral]]) until it stops [[crackling]] in the fire.
#* '''1646''', Sir Thomas Browne, ''Pseudodoxia Epidemica'', Folio 2007, p. 333:
#*: so will it come to pass in a pot of salt, although '''decrepitated'''; and so also in a pot of Snow.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of [[salts]] and [[minerals]], to [[crackle]] when heated, indicating a sudden breakdown of their particles.
#* {{quote-journal|en|magazine=Magazine of Popular Science, and Journal of the Useful Arts|year=1837|passage=It is, however, remarkable, that the greater number of bodies which '''decrepitate''', are really anhydrous and fixed, such as sulphate of potash, sulphate of barytes, chloride of sodium, &c.|page=77}}
#* '''1907''', {{w|M. M. Pattison Muir}}, ''A History of Chemical Theories and Laws'', [https://archive.org/details/historyofchemica00muirrich/page/202/mode/1up?view=theater p. 202:]
#*:That substance was called salt, because, according to some authors, it is obtained by the action of the sun (''sol'') on sea-water, according to others, because it '''decrepitates''' in the fire (''exsilire''=to crackle and spring about).

